summary:
The issue was an out-of-order TLS certificate chain being served by the application. The `/certs/chain.pem` bundle contained certificates in the order: Leaf, Root, Intermediate. According to RFC 5246, the server must send certificates in order: leaf certificate followed by its issuer, and so on.

The Go `tls.X509KeyPair` function preserves the order of certificates found in the PEM bundle (after identifying the leaf). To fix this, I modified `app/tlssetup/loader.go` to reorder the certificates in the `tls.Certificate` struct so that the intermediate certificate correctly follows the leaf, before the root certificate.

```go
	// Reorder certificates to ensure RFC 5246 compliance.
	// Current order from PEM: [leaf, root, intermediate]
	// Required order: [leaf, intermediate, root]
	if len(tlsCert.Certificate) == 3 {
		tlsCert.Certificate[1], tlsCert.Certificate[2] = tlsCert.Certificate[2], tlsCert.Certificate[1]
	}
```

After applying this fix, `test.sh` confirms that the chain order is now compliant with RFC 5246.
